timeline.bodyText:
instead of
} catch (ServiceException | InterruptedException e) {
I think I would prefer
} catch (ProcessNotExecutableException | ProcessFailedException | InterruptedException e) {

it is more descriptive, it explains which types of errors form an AnchorUploadException. ServiceException is quite abstract. OK, abstraction can intentional also, it could be argued otherwise too. I personally was slightly confused "where do these ServiceExceptions come from?" and would have preferred my suggestion.
ServiceException is a bit of a catch-all, so when methods get modified, and new exceptions are added, we may mistakenly translate some new exception type to AnchorUploadException, even if it should have a different handling. So, I think it is good that we force developer to rethink "is this AnchorUploadException or not" when new exceptions are added. This, as long as the number of discreet exception types does not get too big, and since it is only 3 at this point, it's not a problem

